Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't think we should open changing ownership like that. I do agree that changing owner can be useful in some cases, but we do not allow anyone even share images with others without approval from the receiving end. We should not allow spamming images via ownership either.

Patch Set 1:

Stuart,

I don't think I said that we must not make owner change possible. What I said was that we should not just bluntly remove restriction to do that. You don't think there is any possible vulnerabilities opened by this change as it is?

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@Fei Long Wang

Functionally testing, this seemed to work fine for an admin, but a regular user seemed to get a 404 (rather than the current 403, which is probably better) if they try to change ownership of one of their images.

404 Not Found: No image found with ID 8bb407dd-f311-49bc-a1ab-d1d5fb0a6078 (HTTP 404)

Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

@Erno

Thanks.

Interesting that you saw a 403 rather than 404. Could be that my test system is a bit out of date (I'll remove my -1 on that assumption).

I'm not sure there's much that can be done to guard against setting to a non-existent user (we don't do anything in v1 or the membership stuff for example).

Patch Set 1:

I think I'm fine with this change after there is APIImpact added to the commit message.

Indeed my main concern was the scenario I thought I was able to produce with changing the owner as image owner (non-admin) where it looked like one could add own user as member and then change the owner to something that does not exists to go around quota limitations and possibly flood a) somebody else's quota or b) the back end storage. Fortunately neither of these were the case.

Patch Set 1:

Thanks for the comments, guy. But I'm wondering if the APIImpact is suitable for this case. This fix doesn't change any contact/interface/signature of Glance rest API. It just make it a little bit open/consist. I'd like to see the others comments.

Are there existing tests which check that a regular user gets a 403 for this operation (whether they own the image or it is shared with them or public)?
If not, do folks agree that they are probably needed?

Also, are there cross-owner checks, eg that an admin can update an image they don't own?

Sorry if this is a pain, but we do need to be sure about who can do what here.

Thanks!
